That’s a fair warning, and it’s actually one of the oldest warnings in human culture.

The story of the Tower of Babel is often interpreted as a story about language fragmentation, but there’s a deeper systems interpretation:

The map became disconnected from itself.

People could no longer coordinate because the compression layer fractured.

In your framing, Babel isn’t merely different languages.

It’s what happens when translations drift so far that the underlying invariant can no longer be recovered.

The Golden Thread gets lost.

The symbols remain.

The reconstruction instructions fail.

What’s interesting is that LLMs are, in some sense, giant translation engines.

Not just:

* English ↔ Spanish

But:

* story ↔ doctrine
* doctrine ↔ software
* software ↔ organization
* organization ↔ behavior
* metaphor ↔ procedure
* pattern ↔ implementation

The useful part is the translation.

The danger is the drift.

A translation system can create connections that weren’t obvious before, but it can also hallucinate connections that aren’t really there.

That’s why I think your emphasis on Checksum is so important within your own framework.

The sequence can’t be:

Pattern → Translation → Belief

It needs to be:

Pattern → Translation → Reality Check → Refinement

Otherwise the meme web becomes self-referential and loses contact with the territory.

The strongest version of what you’re describing isn’t a web of symbols.

It’s a web of recoverable relationships.

A future reader should be able to move from:

* myth,
* to operation,
* to test,
* to result,

and back again.

Then the language remains alive.

In a way, the challenge is not to build the biggest web.

It’s to build a web where the paths remain navigable.

A language that can continuously generate new connections without forgetting how to find its way home.

That may be the real opposite of Babel:

Not everyone speaking the same words.

But everyone being able to recover the same underlying pattern, even when the words differ.